Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In an attempt to gather additional information regarding the playlist and their inner consistency an exploratory analysis is being performed.

First a general overview of all basic features is delivered. Second additional features [such as artist and track popularity] are being computed to offer a holistic view on the characteristics of this playlist aggregation.

Overview¶

Before diving into the data, here are some pointers from Spotify's official readme file regarding the features:

Data Set¶

Each slice file is a JSON dictionary with two fields: info and playlists.

info Field¶

The info field is a dictionary that contains general information about the particular slice:

  • slice - the range of slices that in in this particular file - such as 0-999
  • version - - the current version of the MPD (which should be v1)
  • generated_on - a timestamp indicating when the slice was generated.

playlists field¶

This is an array that typically contains 1,000 playlists.

Playlist JSON¶

Each playlist is a dictionary that contains the following fields:

  • pid - integer - playlist id - the MPD ID of this playlist. This is an integer between 0 and 999,999.
  • name - string - the name of the playlist
  • description - optional string - if present, the description given to the playlist. Note that user-provided playlist descrptions are a relatively new feature of Spotify, so most playlists do not have descriptions.
  • modified_at - seconds - timestamp (in seconds since the epoch) when this playlist was last updated. Times are rounded to midnight GMT of the date when the playlist was last updated.
  • num_artists - the total number of unique artists for the tracks in the playlist.
  • num_albums - the number of unique albums for the tracks in the playlist
  • num_tracks - the number of tracks in the playlist
  • num_followers - the number of followers this playlist had at the time the MPD was created. (Note that the follower count does not including the playlist creator)
  • num_edits - the number of separate editing sessions. Tracks added in a two hour window are considered to be added in a single editing session.
  • duration_ms - the total duration of all the tracks in the playlist (in milliseconds)
  • collaborative - boolean - if true, the playlist is a collaborative playlist. Multiple users may contribute tracks to a collaborative playlist.
  • tracks - an array of information about each track in the playlist. Each element in the array is a dictionary with the following fields:
    • track_name - the name of the track
    • track_uri - the Spotify URI of the track
    • album_name - the name of the track's album
    • album_uri - the Spotify URI of the album
    • artist_name - the name of the track's primary artist
    • artist_uri - the Spotify URI of track's primary artist
    • duration_ms - the duration of the track in milliseconds
    • pos - the position of the track in the playlist (zero-based)

How was the dataset built¶

The Million Playist Dataset is created by sampling playlists from the billions of playlists that Spotify users have created over the years. Playlists that meet the following criteria are selected at random:

  • Created by a user that resides in the United States and is at least 13 years old
  • Was a public playlist at the time the MPD was generated
  • Contains at least 5 tracks
  • Contains no more than 250 tracks
  • Contains at least 3 unique artists
  • Contains at least 2 unique albums
  • Has no local tracks (local tracks are non-Spotify tracks that a user has on their local device)
  • Has at least one follower (not including the creator)
  • Was created after January 1, 2010 and before December 1, 2017
  • Does not have an offensive title
  • Does not have an adult-oriented title if the playlist was created by a user under 18 years of age

Additionally, some playlists have been modified as follows:

  • Potentially offensive playlist descriptions are removed
  • Tracks added on or after November 1, 2017 are removed

def open_json(file_name):
    """
    Helper method to open and return json
    file.
    
    Parameters:
    --------------
    file_name: string representation of path to json file
    
    Returns:
    --------------
    tmp_playlist_json: json object

Generate Lookup Dictionaries for Track and Artist URIs¶

To make it easier to interpret and to investigate, we'll create two dictionaries that map a specific track or artist uri with their string representation.

In [23]:
def store_new_mapping(dic, key, content):
    """
    Helper method that stores a new key if not existent yet.
    
    Parameters:
    --------------
    dic:        storage dictionary
    key:        key to be mapped
    content:    mapping content
    
    Returns:
    --------------
    None - but stores key and content in mapping dictionary
    """
    if key not in dic:
        dic[key] = content
In [24]:
def create_artist_and_track_lookup_dicts(artist_uri_to_string, track_uri_to_string, playlist_collection):
    """
    Iterates over playlist in playlist collection and scans all tracks of 
    each playlist for their artist and track uris. Each URI is being stored
    with the string representation.
    
    Parameters:
    --------------
    artist_uri_to_string:  storage dictionary that holds the artist uri 
                           to string mapping <key: string>
    track_uri_to_string:   storage dictionary that holds the track uri 
                           to string mapping
    playlist_collection:   list of playlist dictionaries
    
    Returns:
    --------------
    None - but stores mapping in respective dictionaries
    """
    for playlist in playlist_collection['playlists']:
        for track in playlist['tracks']:
            store_new_mapping(artist_uri_to_string, track['artist_uri'], track['artist_name'])
            store_new_mapping(track_uri_to_string, track['track_uri'], track['track_name'])
In [25]:
def get_artist_and_track_lookup_dicts(recompute=False):
    """
    Iteration method leveraging create_artist_and_track_lookup_dicts method 
    to aggregate information out of all playlist collections.
    
    Parameters:
    --------------
    recompute:    bool flag determining whether precomputed results should be used or not
    
    Returns:
    --------------
    artist_uri_to_string:    dict mapping artist uris to their string representation
    track_uri_to_string:     dict mapping track uris to their string representation
    """
    if recompute:
        artist_uri_to_string = {}
        track_uri_to_string = {}

        total_files = len(os.listdir(PLAYLIST_FOLDER))
        counter = 0
        for playlist_file in os.listdir(PLAYLIST_FOLDER):
            counter += 1
            clear_output(wait=True) 
            print ("Working on slice {} ({:.2f} %) (File Name:  {} || Total Slices: {})".format(
                counter, (counter / total_files) * 100, playlist_file, total_files))
            playlist_collection = open_json(os.path.join(PLAYLIST_FOLDER, playlist_file))
            create_artist_and_track_lookup_dicts(artist_uri_to_string, track_uri_to_string, playlist_collection)
        
        write_dict(artist_uri_to_string, os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, 'artist_uri_to_string.pckl'))
        write_dict(track_uri_to_string, os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, 'track_uri_to_string.pckl'))
    else:
        artist_uri_to_string = open_dict(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, 'artist_uri_to_string.pckl'))
        track_uri_to_string = open_dict(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, 'track_uri_to_string.pckl'))
    
    return artist_uri_to_string, track_uri_to_string

def get_playlist_filename_and_idx(pid):
    """
    Constructs playlist filename and playlist index within file from playlist id
    """
    idx = pid % 1000
    filename_root = int(pid / float(1000)) * 1000
    filename = 'mpd.slice.{}-{}.json'.format(filename_root, filename_root+999)
    return (filename, idx)

def get_playlist(pid, tracks_only=False):
    if pid < 0 or pid > 999999:
        raise ValueError('Playlist id out of range (has to be within 0 and 999999)')
    file_name, playlist_idx = get_playlist_filename_and_idx(pid)
    playlist_json = open_json(os.path.join(PLAYLIST_FOLDER, file_name))
    playlist_collection = playlist_json['playlists']
    if tracks_only:
        return playlist_collection[playlist_idx]['tracks']
    return playlist_collection[playlist_idx]

Compute Popularity of Songs and Artists¶

All occurances of tracks and artists in the playlist are being counted. This can be used as a popularity proxy for a given track.

def count_or_one(dic, element):
    """
    Counts occurences and stores the result in a dictionary.
    
    Parameters:
    --------------
    dic: dictionary containing the counts
    element: key to be found in dic
    
    Returns:
    --------------
    None - but stores updates & results in dic
    """
    if element not in dic:
        dic[element] = 1
    else:
        dic[element] += 1
In [36]:
def count_artists_and_tracks(artist_popularity_dict, track_popularity_dict, playlist_collection):
    """
    Iterates over playlist in playlist collection and scans all tracks of 
    each playlist for their artist and track uris. These occurences
    are being counted to determine a popularity proxy for each URI.
    
    Parameters:
    --------------
    artist_popularity_dict: storage dictionary that holds the artist uri counts
    track_popularity_dict: storage dictionary that holds the track uri counts
    playlist_collection: list of playlist dictionaries
    
    Returns:
    --------------
    None - but stores counts in respective dictionaries
    """
    for playlist in playlist_collection['playlists']:
        for track in playlist['tracks']:
            artist = track['artist_uri']
            track = track['track_uri']
            count_or_one(artist_popularity_dict, artist)
            count_or_one(track_popularity_dict, track)

In [38]:
# iterate over playlist collections
def create_popularity_dicts(recompute=False):
    """
    Iteration method leveraging count_artists_and_tracks method 
    to aggregate information out of all playlist collections.
    
    Parameters:
    --------------
    recompute:    bool flag determining whether precomputed results should be used or not
    
    Returns:
    --------------
    artist_popularity_dict:    dict mapping artist uris to their popularity count in all playlists
    track_popularity_dict:     dict mapping track uris to their popularity count in all playlists
    """
    artist_popularity_dict_name = 'artist_popularity_dict.pckl'
    track_popularity_dict_name = 'track_popularity_dict.pckl'
    
    if recompute:
        artist_popularity_dict = {}
        track_popularity_dict = {}
        total_files = len(os.listdir(PLAYLIST_FOLDER))
        counter = 0
        for playlist_file in os.listdir(PLAYLIST_FOLDER):
            counter += 1
            clear_output(wait=True) 
            print ("Working on slice {} ({:.2f} %) (File Name:  {} || Total Slices: {})".format(
                counter, (counter / total_files) * 100, playlist_file, total_files))
            playlist_collection = open_json(os.path.join(PLAYLIST_FOLDER, playlist_file))
            count_artists_and_tracks(artist_popularity_dict, track_popularity_dict, playlist_collection)

        # store dicts
        with open(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, track_popularity_dict_name), 'wb') as f:
            pickle.dump(track_popularity_dict, f)

        with open(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, artist_popularity_dict_name), 'wb') as f:
            pickle.dump(artist_popularity_dict, f)
    else:
        with open(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, artist_popularity_dict_name), 'rb') as f:
            artist_popularity_dict = pickle.load(f)
        with open(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, track_popularity_dict_name), 'rb') as f:
            track_popularity_dict = pickle.load(f)
    
    return artist_popularity_dict, track_popularity_dict

def get_uri_to_songname_and_artist_dict(recompute=False):
    if not os.path.exists(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, 'uri_to_artist_and_songname_full.pckl')) or recompute:
        uri_to_artist_and_songname = {}
        total_files = len(os.listdir(PLAYLIST_FOLDER))
        counter = 0
        for playlist_file in os.listdir(PLAYLIST_FOLDER):
            counter += 1
            clear_output(wait=True) 
            print ("Working on slice {} ({:.2f} %) (File Name:  {} || Total Slices: {})".format(
                counter, (counter / total_files) * 100, playlist_file, total_files))
            playlist_collection = open_json(os.path.join(PLAYLIST_FOLDER, playlist_file))
            for playlist in playlist_collection['playlists']:
                for track in playlist['tracks']:
                    if track['track_uri'] not in uri_to_artist_and_songname:
                        uri_to_artist_and_songname[track['track_uri']] = (
                            track['artist_name'], track['track_name'])
        write_dict(uri_to_artist_and_songname, os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, 'uri_to_artist_and_songname_full.pckl'))
        return uri_to_artist_and_songname
    else:
        return open_dict(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, 'uri_to_artist_and_songname_full.pckl'))

The assumption of a high skew when it comes to popularity holds true for this data set as well. Both density distributions for tracks and artists show a few successful items and a very heavy long tail.

Investigating the long-tail¶

To see how rich the long-tail really is, let's take a look at some values of rare tracks and artists.

In [91]:
def get_longtail(full_df, ltype, title=None, cutoff=10, figsize=(6, 4)):
    """
    Investigates the longtail by creating buckets of the least popular items.
    
    Parameters:
    -------------
    full_df: list with popularity counts
    ltype: can be 'artist' or 'track' determining which uri-class should be investigated.
    cutoff: int that determines the amount of popularity to be deleted
    
    Returns:
    -------------
    None - but prints summary and plots barplot of longtail
    """
    element_buckets = []
    for i in range(1, cutoff+1):
        tmp_element_buckets = [x for x in full_df if x < i+1 and x > i-1]
        element_buckets.append(len(tmp_element_buckets))
    element_buckets.append(len([x for x in full_df if x > cutoff]))
    
    if ltype in ['artist', 'track']:
        print ("{:,} {}s of {:,} appear only once in a playlist ({:.2f} %). \n \
           {:,} {}s ({:.2f} %) appear {} times or fewer.".format(
        element_buckets[0], 
        ltype,
        len(full_df), 
        element_buckets[0] / len(full_df) * 100,
        np.sum(element_buckets[:cutoff]),
        ltype,
        np.sum(element_buckets[:cutoff]) / len(full_df) * 100,
        cutoff))
        x_label = 'Playlist appearances'
        if not title:
            title = 'Number of times an {} appears in a playlist.'.format(ltype)
    else:
        x_label = ltype
    
    fig_elements_longtail, ax_elements_longtail = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
    ax_elements_longtail.set_title(title)
    ax_elements_longtail.set_ylabel('Amount of {}s'.format(ltype))
    ax_elements_longtail.set_xlabel(x_label)
    labels = [str(x) for x in range(1,cutoff+1)]
    labels.append('>{}'.format(cutoff))
    sns.barplot(x=labels, y=element_buckets, ax=ax_elements_longtail)

The MPD-Artist Longtail¶

As mentioned above a feature that needs to be taken into account are skews within the data set. Any co-occurence based algorithms might fail to perform well, if there is not enough information within the item representations. Some studys have shown that using a different approach for long-tail predictions yield better performance than others. One potential way of handling these characteristics of playlist collections could be popularity based pre-filtering.

In [92]:
get_longtail(all_artists_popularity, ltype='artist', cutoff=15)

101,885 artists of 295,860 appear only once in a playlist (34.44 %). 
            228,433 artists (77.21 %) appear 15 times or fewer.

More than a third of all artists appear only once in a playlist. Chances are very high that a co-occurence driven approach will heavily overfit to the one playlist this artist is in. The plot above shows another property of this particular dataset. The skews are heavy in both directions. There are a few artists that have a lot of appearances and a lot of artists that have none.

The MPD-Track Longtail¶

Similar to the characteristics of the artist distribution, the lion-share of tracks has less than 15 playlist placements. In fact the skew is a little bit more severe, which makes sense since the overall population is way larger. With less than 12 % of all tracks appearing more than 15 times in a playlist we need to find a way to model rare tracks and show their similarity to each other.

Compute Popularity Focus of Playlists¶

In this section the popularity of tracks and artists will be broken down on a playlist level. It might be interesting to see how popularity aggregations change per playlist and whether it plays an important role in the inner consistency of playlists. First all tracks and artists of every playlist will be matched with the earlier computed popularity score. At the same time, median and average values will be computed as well since playlists differ in length.

In [94]:
def get_playlist_artist_track_popularity(columns,
                                         artist_popularity_dict, 
                                         track_popularity_dict, 
                                         playlist_collection):
    """
    Method that iterates over a playlist collection and retrieves all potential information 
    to store in one list of lists. This list can be used to create a well-formed pandas
    DataFrame.
    
    Parameters:
    ---------------
    columns: list storing all available and additional features for playlists
    artist_popularity_dict: lookup dict for artist popularity metrics
    artist_popularity_dict: lookup dict for track popularity metrics
    playlist_collection: retrieved playlist json
    
    Returns:
    ---------------
    tmp_playlist_list: list of lists every list containing features of a playlist
    columns: list of column names
    """
    tmp_playlist_list = []
    for playlist in playlist_collection['playlists']:          
        tmp_popularity = []
        tmp_track_pop = []
        tmp_artist_pop = []
        track_count = 0
        if not columns:
            columns = [x for x in playlist.keys() if 'tracks' not in str(x) and 'description' not in str(x)]
            columns.extend(
                ['artist_popularity', 'artist_popularity_mean', 'artist_popularity_median', 
                 'track_popularity', 'track_popularity_mean', 'track_popularity_median', 
                 'description', 'num_tracks'])
        tmp_playlist_features = [playlist[x] for x in playlist.keys() if 'tracks' not in str(x) and 'description' not in str(x)]
        for track in playlist['tracks']:
            track_count += 1
            artist = track['artist_uri']
            track = track['track_uri']
            tmp_artist_pop.append(artist_popularity_dict[artist])
            tmp_track_pop.append(track_popularity_dict[track])
        tmp_playlist_features.extend(
            [np.sum(tmp_artist_pop), np.mean(tmp_artist_pop), np.median(tmp_artist_pop),
             np.sum(tmp_track_pop), np.mean(tmp_track_pop), np.median(tmp_track_pop)])
        tmp_playlist_features.append(playlist['description'] if 'description' in playlist.keys() else None)
        tmp_playlist_features.append(track_count)
        tmp_playlist_list.append(tmp_playlist_features)
    return tmp_playlist_list, columns
In [95]:
def get_playlist_df(recompute):
    """
    Iteration method to retrieve and store playlist features.
    
    Parameters:
    ----------------
    recompute:  bool flag indicating whether to load data from precomputed 
                results or retrieve from json objects
    Returns:
    ----------------
    playlist_df:  DataFrame containing features of playlists
    """
    if recompute:
        playlist_popularity = []
        total_files = len(os.listdir(PLAYLIST_FOLDER))
        counter = 0
        columns = None
        for playlist_file in os.listdir(PLAYLIST_FOLDER):
            counter += 1
            clear_output(wait=True) 
            print ("Working on slice {} ({:.2f} %) (File Name:  {} || Total Slices: {})".format(
                counter, (counter / total_files) * 100, playlist_file, total_files))
            playlist_collection = open_json(os.path.join(PLAYLIST_FOLDER, playlist_file))
            tmp_playlist_popularity, columns = get_playlist_artist_track_popularity(columns, artist_popularity_dict, track_popularity_dict, playlist_collection)
            playlist_popularity.extend(tmp_playlist_popularity)
        playlist_df = pd.DataFrame(playlist_popularity, columns=columns)
        playlist_df.to_csv(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, 'playlist_df.csv'))
    else:
        playlist_df = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(RESULTS_FOLDER, 'playlist_df.csv'), index_col=0)
    return playlist_df

    corr, p_val = stats.pearsonr(playlist_df['num_artists'], playlist_df[feature])
    print ('num_artists -> {}: correleation: {:.3f} (p: {})'.format(feature, corr, p_val))

    corr, p_val))

num_artists -> num_albums: correleation: 0.956 (p: 0.0)
num_artists -> num_tracks: correleation: 0.818 (p: 0.0)
num_albums -> num_tracks: correleation: 0.900 (p: 0.0)

The calculations verify a strong and highly significant correlation between those features. It looks like following statements hold true:

  • A playlist with a high number of artists has a higher number of albums
  • Playlists that have a higher number of artists have more tracks
  • Playlists that hold more individual albums hold more individual tracks

We therefore might be able to compress some of this information down the road if needed.

def find_emojis(topic_list):
    emoji_to_idx = {}
    total_count = 0
    emoji_counts = {}
    for idx, s in enumerate(topic_list):
        ems = re.findall(u'[\U0001f600-\U0001f650]', s)
        count = len(ems)
        for e in ems:
            count_or_one(emoji_counts, e)
            if e in emoji_to_idx:
                if idx not in emoji_to_idx[e]:
                    emoji_to_idx[e].append(idx)
            else:
                emoji_to_idx[e] = [idx]
        total_count += count
    return emoji_counts, emoji_to_idx, total_count

TF-IDF¶

The tf-idf score determines the importance of a term in a given document (in our case the title or description) for that document with respect of its frequency in the overall corpus. Since we're dealing with a slim amount of information in the titles and a sparse dataset with regards of descriptions it might be tough to leverage this method completely. Nevertheless, we'll perform a quick preprocessing and tf-idf scoring to see whether there are some interesting results in the titles.

In [168]:
def preprocess_text_to_lemmas(topics):
    """
    Turns list of documents in to list of lemmas by removing stopwords,
    lowering, tokenizing and lemmatizing the words. 
    
    Parameters:
    --------------
    topics:        list of documents
    
    Returns:
    --------------
    return_list:   list of lemmas 
    """
    engl_stopwords = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')
    return_list = []
    topics = [x.lower() for x in topics]
    for t in topics:
        tokens = [x for x in tokenizer.tokenize(t) if x not in engl_stopwords]
        for idx, token in enumerate(tokens):
            tokens[idx] = lemmatizer.lemmatize(token)
        return_list.append(tokens)
    return return_list
In [169]:
lemma_list = preprocess_text_to_lemmas(topics)
In [170]:
def get_tf_idf(documents, verbose=False):
    """
    Calculate tf-idf score of list of documents.
    
    Parameters:
    --------------
    documents:      list of documents
    
    Returns:
    --------------
    term_to_pids:                    dict mapping a certain term to a list of ids in which it occurs
    document_corpus_frequencies:     dict counting the appearance of a term per document (once per doc)
    document_term_frequencies:       dict counting the term frequency in total
    tfidf_doc_score:                 dict mapping a document id to the term: tf-idf score dictionary
    """
    document_corpus_frequencies = {}
    document_term_frequencies = {}
    term_to_pids = {}

    for idx, doc in enumerate(documents):
        document_term_frequencies[idx] = {}
        for token in doc:
            if token not in document_term_frequencies[idx]:
                if token in term_to_pids:
                    term_to_pids[token].append(idx)
                else:
                    term_to_pids[token] = [idx]
                # make sure there is only one occurance per word
                count_or_one(document_corpus_frequencies, token)
            count_or_one(document_term_frequencies[idx], token)
    
    tfidf_doc_score = {}
    for doc_idx in document_term_frequencies:
        doc = document_term_frequencies[doc_idx]
        for term in doc:
            tf = doc[term] / (len(documents[doc_idx]))            
            idf = np.log10(len(document_term_frequencies) / document_corpus_frequencies[term])
            tfidf = tf * idf
            if verbose:
                print ('term: "{}"\ntf_calc: {}/{}\ntf_val: {}'.format(
                    term, doc[term], len(documents[doc_idx]), tf))
                print ('idf_calc: np.log({}/{})\nidf_val: {}'.format(
                    len(document_term_frequencies),document_corpus_frequencies[term],idf))
                print ('tfidf: {}\n'.format(tfidf))
            if doc_idx not in tfidf_doc_score:
                tfidf_doc_score[doc_idx] = {}
            tfidf_doc_score[doc_idx][term] = tfidf
    return term_to_pids, document_corpus_frequencies, document_term_frequencies, tfidf_doc_score

Bigrams¶

Next we'll investigate bigrams for all titles. Since we know, that the average length of a title is somewhere around 7 characters the information gain from this exercise might be low but since some of the high-ranking tf-idf terms seem chopped it might be interesting to see how this pans out.

In [181]:
def get_most_common_bigrams(lemmas):
    """
    Constructs bigrams based on list of lemmas. 
    """
    bigrams_dict = {}
    for doc_idx, doc in enumerate(lemmas):
        bigrams = []
        for idx in range(len(doc)-1):
            bigrams.append(doc[idx] + '_' + doc[idx+1])
        if bigrams:
            bigrams_dict[doc_idx] = bigrams
    return bigrams_dict

                vmax=1, 
                ax=ax, 
                cmap='coolwarm', 
                annot=True)

Below is a summary of all notable correlations:

  • Playlists that have more edits are longer, contain more artists and more tracks.
  • Playlists that are longer have a higher amount of artists and tracks

All together not the most informative relations that can be derived from this data set.

Summary¶

This fist analysis serves as a good starting point for further investigations and thoughts about sampling methods or important features to stratify on. We'll be using the insights gathered in this document to determine train, validation/development and testing sets.
